<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910327-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>910327-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   IBM New Laptop Computer   To Carry $5,995 List Price</HL><DATE>03/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   IBM T WDC</CO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- International Business Machines Corp. took thewraps off its new laptop computer, marking the computergiant's re-entry into a market that has humbled it in thepast.   The machine, which lists for a steep $5,995, is expectedto be a strong contender in a field dominated by models madeby Toshiba Corp., Compaq Computer Corp. and others. IBM'smachine has a keyboard that is nearly full-size and slopedfor typing comfort. Its hard disk drive is larger thanaverage and the machine can be configured to send and receivefacsimile messages.</LP><TEXT>   IBM, Armonk, N.Y., previously floundered in the market forportable computers, where competitors have proved that speedto market is crucial.   Along with its new laptop, IBM said it would introduce asmaller, lighter &quot;notebook&quot; computer in Japan, to help itgauge customer requirements for a future world-wide version.   Western Digital Corp., meantime, said it has &quot;significant&quot;contracts from IBM to design and build circuit boards for thenew laptop computer.   &quot;We expect the contracts to generate at least $30 millionto $50 million over the next 12 months,&quot; depending on theperformance of IBM's new Personal System/2 Model L40 SXcomputer, a Western Digital spokesman said.   Separately, IBM said it would work with American Telephoneandamp; Telegraph Co. to make the firms' network-managementproducts mesh more easily.</TEXT></DOC>